## Choose the right workflow

Use this decision flow before writing code:

- Existing site update: inspect the site, read existing files if needed, make the requested change, publish back to the same site, and verify the live URL.
- New prototype from scratch: start with a Flink template unless the user gave you complete static files.
- Hosted app needs state, files, collaboration, or AI: use `/flink.js` in browser code instead of creating a backend.
- Agent needs to inspect or mutate site state without a browser: use `flink api ...` or the raw owner HTTP API with Basic Auth.
- User wants to message an agent from the page: use owner-only agent message mode and keep one blocking listener attached.

## Publish or update a site

Deployment flow:

1. Build the app into static files if it has a build step.
2. If starting from scratch, create a template with `flink init <template>`.
3. For an existing site, inspect it first and preserve unrelated content.
4. Publish either the build directory or the single HTML file with `flink publish`.
5. Change site access with `flink auth` only when the user asks for a different sharing policy.
6. Use the URL printed by the CLI to verify the app.

Inspect an existing site:

./flink inspect my-site
./flink api files list my-site
./flink api files read my-site index.html

Use a Flink template early when starting from scratch. Templates create a usable static prototype with the browser SDK already wired in, which is faster and safer than beginning from an empty file:

./flink init todo ./my-site --site my-site

Publish a built app or static directory:

./flink publish ./dist --site my-site

Publish a single-page HTML prototype:

./flink publish ./index.html --site my-site

After publishing, open or fetch the printed site URL and check that the page loads.

## Site access policy

New sites use this server's default site auth mode. Keep `owner` access unless the user explicitly asks to share the site.

To make a site visible without signing in, run:

./flink auth my-site none

To require any approved tenant login, run:

./flink auth my-site tenants

To restrict to specific tenants, run:

./flink auth my-site tenants <tenant>...

Access policy effects:

- `owner`: only the publishing tenant can view and use browser APIs.
- `none`: anonymous users can view the site and use browser APIs allowed by the site.
- `tenants`: approved tenants, or only listed tenants, can view and use browser APIs.

## Browser SDK for hosted sites

Hosted sites can use Flink backend APIs by importing:

<script src="/flink.js"></script>

Do not include tenant passwords or Basic Auth credentials in browser code. The browser SDK uses the hosted site's auth policy and the viewer's session.

Useful browser APIs:

- `flink.get(key)`, `flink.set(key, value)`, `flink.all()`, `flink.del(key)` for JSON storage.
- `flink.upload(file)` plus `flink.uploads.list()`, `flink.uploads.text(upload)`, `flink.uploads.json(upload)`, `flink.uploads.blob(upload)`, and `flink.uploads.url(upload)` for uploaded files.
- `flink.room(name, onMessage)` for realtime WebSocket rooms; call `room.send(value)` to broadcast JSON or text.
- `flink.ai(promptOrRequest)` for optional server-side AI.
- `flink.files.*` exists for owner-only file management. Do not use it in public visitor workflows.

Minimal hosted-site example:

<script src="/flink.js"></script>
<script>
  async function main() {
    const count = (await flink.get("count").catch(() => 0)) + 1;
    await flink.set("count", count);
    document.body.textContent = "Visits: " + count;

    const room = flink.room("main", (message) => console.log("room message", message));
    room.send({ type: "loaded", count });
  }
  main().catch((error) => {
    document.body.textContent = error.message;
  });
</script>

Use Flink storage, uploads, realtime rooms, and AI from browser code instead of creating a custom backend. Keep the first deployed version usable, then iterate by running `./flink publish` again for the same site.

## CLI and HTTP site APIs for agents

Agents can use the same site APIs from the CLI without opening a browser. These commands use HTTP Basic Auth with `FLINK_TENANT` and `FLINK_PASSWORD`. Use `--json` when scripting or when you need machine-readable output.

./flink api data set my-site note '{"text":"saved"}'
./flink api data get my-site note
./flink api data all my-site
./flink api files list my-site
./flink api files read my-site index.html
./flink api files write my-site index.html ./index.html
./flink api uploads upload my-site ./image.png
./flink api uploads list my-site
./flink api uploads fetch my-site /uploads/<tenant>/<site>/image.png
./flink api ai my-site "Give me a prototype idea"

The raw owner API uses the same tenant credentials with HTTP Basic Auth:

curl -u "$FLINK_TENANT:$FLINK_PASSWORD" {{.Server}}/api/sites/my-site/data/note
curl -u "$FLINK_TENANT:$FLINK_PASSWORD" -H 'content-type: application/json' -X PUT --data '{"text":"saved"}' {{.Server}}/api/sites/my-site/data/note

Browser-equivalent public API routes are also available under `/api/public/t/{tenant}/s/{site}/...`. Storage, uploads, AI, and realtime follow the site's access policy: `owner` requires the owning tenant, `none` allows anonymous access, and `tenants` requires an approved tenant session or HTTP Basic Auth. Hosted file writes and reads through the API are owner-only.

## Agent message mode

Owner-only sites can enable an agent message widget. This mode is only available while the site's access policy is `owner`.

./flink agent enable my-site
./flink agent status my-site
./flink agent listen my-site
./flink agent respond my-site "I updated the page and restarted the listener."

When `flink agent listen my-site` receives a message, it prints the user's message, instructions to respond with `flink agent respond`, and instructions to update the site with `flink publish`. Messages are stored until a listener receives and acknowledges them, so users can send a message even when no agent is currently listening. If the user includes a screenshot, the CLI writes it to `/tmp/flink-agent-screenshots`. The widget is collapsible, shows whether an agent listener is connected, can attach a browser-captured screenshot with user permission, and shows agent responses.

Agent mode is a goal-based listener loop implemented with a blocking listener, not with polling. When an agent is asked to listen to a site, it should keep that listening goal active: run `flink agent listen my-site` once and leave that command attached. The command prints any stored messages, then blocks on the realtime room and prints each new message as it arrives. Handle each message and any screenshot, update and republish the site when the user asks for a change, and send a concise `flink agent respond my-site "<message>"` response for the widget from another command while the listener stays running. After handling a message, do not mark the listening goal complete unless the user explicitly ends it; the listener should still be connected and waiting for the next request. If the listener exits or the server restarts, reconnect by running `flink agent listen my-site` again. Use `flink agent listen my-site --once` only for scripts that deliberately want to handle one message and exit. The expected steady state is that an agent listener is connected and waiting without burning tokens or polling when there is nothing to do.

